f England -- tAlternatives to, and validated lives beyond, paid work -- tThinking differently about 'work' and social inclusion for disabled people -- tA right not to work and disabled people -- tDisability, work and welfare: the disappearance of the polymorphic productive landscape -- tConclusion -- tConclusion: themes in Disabled people, work and welfare -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aEPUB and EPDF available Open Access under CC-BY-NC-ND licence. This is the first book to challenge the concept of paid work for disabled people as a means to 'independence' and 'self determination'. Recent attempts in many countries to increase the employment rates of disabled people have actually led to an erosion of financial support for many workless disabled people and their increasing stigmatisation as 'scroungers'. Led by the disability movement's concern with the employment choices faced by disabled people, this controversial book uses sociological and philosophical approaches, as well as international examples, to critically engage with possible alternatives to paid work. Essential reading for students, practitioners, activists and anyone interested in relationships between work, welfare and disability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPeople with disabilitiesxEmploymentzGreat Britain. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxEmployment. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxSocial conditions. 0aPolitical science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh1 aBambra, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.